<subSubSection id="519D557304CC164916138FBAB7B016C0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="244DC712E68B3E15B5B7646DFE83BA9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AC81215ACC41611F705F10F0F0A99E33" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The female paratype of sister species 
<taxonomicName id="C05BB03A1557F85D669722D83B331A9B" family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. electus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="electus">
<emphasis id="D75BE7F6C93FC32A01B921925A199BF5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. electus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, collected from Gaoligongshan, was considered of doubtful identity by 
<bibRefCitation id="9AD3D22E6BA02166004F8E9B07C756D3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.664.11881" author="Brunke, AJ" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 97" refId="B1" refString="Brunke, AJ, 2017. A revision of the Oriental species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). ZooKeys 664: 1 - 97, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.664.11881" title="A revision of the Oriental species of Bolitogyrus Chevrolat (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Staphylininae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.664.11881" volume="664" year="2017">Brunke (2017)</bibRefCitation>
based on it being a western outlier from the main distribution of that species. A series of males and females from the same locality indicate that this female paratype is really 
<taxonomicName id="3B682AEB9C8E6FB8EE1304F874111177" family="Staphylinidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. uncus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="uncus">
<emphasis id="5D462AC41C9A40320263C896877A97BC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">B. uncus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and that these two species are probably separated allopatrically by the Salween River valley (
<normalizedToken id="0800507BA8338CF9A5EF4701E8594B01" originalValue="“Nujiang”">&quot;Nujiang&quot;</normalizedToken>
in China).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
